choices.text:
the election of Ian Khama to the presidency of this landlocked country in S.Africa. The 43yr old Military Chief toppled the popular and incumbent President, Festus Mogae. Mr Khama’s popularity cannot be overemphasized. In short, he was 2nd candidate popular with the School Girls vote. Botswana over the period of elections under Festus Mogae witnessed low voter participation rates, suggesting that his popularity was fading fast with the nation. It is worthy to note that of the 448,000 registered voters, a whooping 57% voted for Ian Khama, a whopping majority amongst the registered voters. Apparently, his overwhelming support came from the marginalised ethnic groups who felt neglected and discriminated against by Mr Mogae’s government. This fueled support for Mr Khama who promised fair and equitable distribution of the country’s wealth. I am sure this move by the ethnic Sanks repelled much support from the black population who do not want to see more power concentrated in the hands of the Sanks; the leadership position more or less is dominated by the Sanks even for those in the ruling party.

From time to time the Central and southern African Nations tend to use the Marginalised group within the country ideology to push govern their leadership interests, thereby appealing to the sensitive issues of the nation to garner support. What is democracy all about if a certain ethnicity is ruled by a particular ethnicity.

The election of Mr Khama evoked some mixed reactions
